Aditu no-Sa'onserei|Aditu	Known among Erkynlanders by the honorific Lady, a Sitha and one of the youngest of the immortal Sithi people, born after the fall of Asu'a. She is the daughter of Shima'onari and Likimeya and the sister of Jiriki. Slender in build, she is recognisable by her golden skin, golden cat-like eyes, and lavender-dyed hair. In character she is warm, curious, and openly fond of children — and notably unbothered by the conventions around clothing that humans observe. She counts Simon among her close friends, and is on familiar terms with the scholar Tanahaya.
Amerasu y'Senditu no'e-Sa'onserei|Amerasu|Amerasu Ship-Born|First Grandmother	Known as First Grandmother among the Sithi and as Amerasu Ship-Born, one of the most revered of the immortal Sithi people — an ancient wise-woman of exceptional standing. To some mortals she is known as the Lady of the Wood or Queen of Fairies. She reigned in the great Sithi city of Asu'a beside her husband Iyu'unigato, and after its fall helped lead her people to the hidden refuge of Jao é-Tinukai'i, of which she became mistress. In her long stewardship of that realm she received mortal visitors on rare occasion. In bearing she is slender and regal, with a high noble brow, startlingly golden eyes, white uncolored hair, and an amber translucence to her skin. Her manner is wise, stern, and touched with mild sarcasm.
An'nai	A Sitha and one of Jiriki's most trusted companions, serving as his lieutenant and hunting partner. He has black hair that shines with a green hue, and amber eyes.
Aspitis Previs	A Nabbanai nobleman, Count of Eadne and master of Prevan House. A close friend of Benigaris, he moves in the highest circles of Nabbanai power and serves as paymaster of the Fire Dancers. His manner is outwardly charming, though beneath the courtly surface he is entitled, ambitious, and cruel.
Benigaris Benidrivine|Benigaris	A Nabbanai nobleman of the powerful Benidrivine house, heir to the Duchy of Nabban. Tall and broad-shouldered, with intense dark eyes beneath thick black brows — a more imposing figure than his father Leobardis, though slightly heavy about the waist. He is the son of Leobardis and Nessalanta, cousin of Miriamele on his mother's side, and brother of Varellan and Antippa.
Binbiniqegabenik|Binabik	A Qanuc troll from the mountain of Mintahoq, and the apprentice of Ookequk, the Singing Man of the Qanuc and a member of the ancient League of the Scroll. Binabik devoted himself to his studies under Ookequk, travelling far across Osten Ard and becoming well versed in its many cultures, histories, and languages, among them Qanuc, Sithi, and Erkynlandish. He is betrothed to Sisqinanamook. Small even by the standards of the Troll folk, he has a round, childlike face with narrow eyes and a wide mouth, and black hair. In character he is kind, intelligent, and possessed of a strong sense of honour; measured and level-headed in discussion, though not without a sardonic edge, and prone to emotional reticence in moments of great distress. He carries a set of bones for divination, poison-tipped blow darts he deploys with deadly accuracy, and a hollow walking stick that conceals a knife. He is the close companion and protector of Simon, and rides the wolf Qantaqa, whom he raised from an abandoned pup.
Bright-Nail|Minneyar|Memory	One of the three legendary swords, also known as Minneyar and Memory. According to accounts linked to Du Svardenvyrd and the Dwarrows, it was forged from the keel of King Elvrit's boat after the Rimmersmen settled in Rimmersgard. Long associated with northern rulers and with Prester John, the sword is one of the great symbols of royal legend in Osten Ard.
Cadrach|Cadrach ec-Crannhyr|Padreic ec-Crannhyr|Padreic	A Hernystiri monk and scholar, often called Brother Cadrach, born in the ancient city of Crannhyr. Stout and pink-faced, with small sharp grey eyes and a monk's tonsure, he is clever, cynical, cautious, fearful, and inclined toward drink. Also known as Padreic, he is a man of uncertain religious order and dubious honesty, able to win the confidence of companions while remaining hard to trust. His learning is considerable: he has knowledge of Osten Ard, natural philosophy, mechanical workings, herblore, and aspects of the Art, giving him a depth that sits uneasily beside his evasions and shabby wandering life.
Camaris-Sá-Vinitta|Camaris|Camaris Benidrivine	A legendary Nabbanai knight, born into the royal Benidrivine house as the son of Benidrivis-sá-Vinitta and elder brother of Duke Leobardis. Wielder of the great sword Thorn, he was High King Prester John's closest companion and greatest champion, widely regarded as the mightiest and most skilled warrior ever to walk Osten Ard. Their friendship began in unlikely fashion on the battlefield of Nearlaugh, where Camaris, then fifteen, took up his uncle Ardrivus's sword against the conquering John; after a duel that ended in mutual respect, the two became inseparable. Though undisputed in his martial gifts, Camaris was by nature a pacifist who viewed fighting as a necessary burden rather than a glory. He was deeply religious, calm, and marked by a profound, inward sorrow. He bore the sword Thorn and the hunting horn Ti-tuno, also called Cellian, crafted at Mezutu'a from the fang of the dragon Hidohebhi.
Charystra	The Perdruinese proprietress of the inn Pelippa's Bowl in Kwanitupul, which she inherited from her aunt Xorastra. She is jut-jawed and combative in bearing, and her character is defined by greed, selfishness, and a chronic tendency to whine. She is a poor cook but a skilled negotiator where money is concerned. An Aedonite, she has little of her aunt's charitable spirit and a great deal of contempt for the establishment she was left with.
Deornoth	A young Erkynlander knight in his late twenties, knighted by Prince Josua and entirely devoted to his service. From a Hewenshire freeholding, he grew up working the fields alongside his older brother and sisters; he had little love for his father but holds his mother's memory fondly. Short, lank, dark-haired, and usually wearing a light blue coat, he is kind, loyal, quietly ambitious, and unafraid to speak uncomfortable truths when Josua needs to hear them. He is an accomplished swordsman and skilled horseman, and is sometimes called the Prince's Right Hand.
Dinivan	Father Dinivan is a Nabbanai Aedonite priest and the private secretary to Lector Ranessin, head of Mother Church — a position that places him at the intersection of many currents in Osten Ard's affairs. He is also a member of the League of the Scroll. Mostly shaved of head, with a remaining fringe of curly, grey-touched hair, bushy eyebrows, a boyish and homely intelligent face, and a habitual black robe, he makes an unassuming impression that belies the acuity behind it. He is clever, cautious, and jovial in equal measure, and genuinely kind — known by those close to him, including the Princess Miriamele, for offering honest counsel where others bring only flattery. He is versed in some degree of the Art and thoroughly schooled in Aedonite scripture and mythology. He carries the signet ring of Lector Ranessin and wears the golden scroll-and-quill pendant of a Scrollbearer.
Dreosan|Father Dreosan	An Erkynlander Aedonite priest and chaplain at the Hayholt. Known as Father Dreosan, he belongs to the religious household of the royal castle, serving within the same great stronghold that also houses the court, guards, servants, and craftsmen of Erkynland.
Eahlferend	An Erkynlander fisherman, husband of Susanna and father of Simon. His place in the story is tied to the working life around the Hayholt rather than to court rank or arms. His friendship with Doctor Morgenes and his family's connection to a scroll pendant give him a quiet association with Simon's early background.
Ebekah|Efiathe|Rose of Hernysadharc	A Hernystiri woman originally named Efiathe and remembered as the Rose of Hernysadharc. She married Prester John despite being much younger than him and became Queen of Osten Ard. Her place in the royal household connects her to Elias and Josua, and the wiki presents her as a figure whose beauty and presence deeply affected those closest to the High King's court.
Elias	An Erkynlander prince, first-born son of High King Prester John, older brother of Josua, father of Miriamele, Prince Regent of Osten Ard, heir apparent, and Liege-Lord of Meremund. He is large and powerfully built, with black hair, green eyes, a high brow, and a hawklike nose, and he commonly dresses in black and green. Boisterous, forceful, proud, and increasingly temperamental, he is a commanding royal figure whose strained relationship with Josua adds tension to the Hayholt court.
Elispeth	An Erkynlander midwife at the Hayholt. She is remembered for delivering Simon, placing her among the practical servants and household figures connected with his earliest life in the royal castle.
Enfortis	A Nabbanai Imperator who ruled at the time of the fall of Asu'a. His place in the historical record links Nabban's imperial line to the ancient upheaval that ended the Sithi city and shaped the history of the Hayholt.
Eolair	Count of Nad Mullach and kinsman of King Lluth of Hernystir, a Hernystiri nobleman and diplomat of considerable standing. He grew up in native Nad Mullach, at the conjoining of the Inniscrich and Cuihmne rivers in western Hernystir, and was invested with his territories young, pledging loyalty to Lluth when barely twenty-two. He has since served as one of Lluth's most trusted emissaries, earning wide esteem for his bravery and wisdom. Lean-featured, with high thin cheekbones, a high forehead, and long black hair, he carries himself with courtly refinement that conceals, in Isgrimnur's words, a resolve "hard as shield-steel." He is dutiful and composed, and has known Maegwin, Lluth's daughter, since her girlhood. There is speculation that some noble families of Hernystir, Eolair's among them, carry a trace of Sithi blood.
Erkynlander	An inhabitant of Erkynland, counted among the human peoples of Osten Ard. Erkynlanders are associated with Westerling and Erkynlandish speech, and their notable figures include Prince Josua.
Fengbald	Earl of Falshire, an Erkynlander nobleman and one of Elias's closest confidants. He has long black hair and carries himself with the swagger of a man who expects the world to accommodate his ambitions. Ambitious, cruel, and deeply narcissistic, his overconfidence is remarked upon even by those who share his allegiances. At court he is rowdy, aggressive, and eager for advancement, with a reputation that reflects the harsher side of Elias's circle.
Fikolmij	March-thane of the Stallion Clan and supreme ruler of all the Three Thrithings, a position he secured through alliance with Prester John during the Thrithings Wars and holds through fear and brute strength rather than respect. He is a large and formidable man: long black beard knotted into two thick braids, hair faintly striped with silver, a wide frame knotted with muscle, huge hands laden with rings and bracelets, and crooked teeth, appearing at least sixty years of age yet still powerfully fit. Quick to anger, cruel, strong-willed, and deeply duplicitous, he is the father of Vorzheva and Hyara and a hard representative of Thrithings clan power.
Flora and Fauna of Osten Ard	The natural and fantastical life of Osten Ard, ranging from common plants and animals to stranger creatures of legend and lore. Its flora includes croques, fire-poppies, hollyhocks, lilies, marigolds, quickweed, snowdrops, starblooms, sunflowers, wintercap, mistletoe, witchwood, alder, apple, ash, banyan, birch, cedar, fig, hazelnut, hemlock, linden, mangroves, oak, rowan, sand-palm, spruce, oats, wheat, cattails, lutegrass, yellowroot, and corn. Its fauna includes fish, reptiles, amphibians, mammals, birds, insects, dragons, cave borers, ghants, kilpa, and other uncanny creatures.
Freosel	An Erkynlander blacksmith and native of Falshire, associated with Josua's company. Young, stocky, and broad-shouldered, he has the wary heavy-lidded look of a veteran street fighter, a scarred face, a rough voice, a gap in his teeth, and two fingers missing. Clever and plainspoken, he is skilled in metalworking, woodworking, and weapons crafting, and fashioned a short sword for Miriamele. His father was Freobeorn.
Gan Itai	The Niskie kilpa-singer of the ship Eadne Cloud, a member of the Tinukeda'ya people. Ancient, slight, and frail in appearance, she has pale golden skin netted with wrinkles, wide-set dark eyes, a fringe of white hair, and thin brows. Her character is clever, patient, honourable, and deeply kind, though marked by a pervasive tiredness. A great-grandmother many times over from one of the largest Niskie families, she uses kilpa-singing to influence the mood of the sea-creatures called kilpa, ordinarily to keep them at bay.
Guthwulf	Earl of Utanyeat and High King's Hand to Elias, an Erkynlander nobleman who has been Elias's close friend since youth, sharing battles and adventures across many years. Green-eyed, with greying hair cut short, he is clever, shrewd, and deeply loyal, though intolerant of disrespect from those beneath him. He served Elias faithfully through the early years of his reign, and Elias has privately declared him the only man he truly trusts. Guthwulf, for his part, watches the growing influence of Pryrates over the king with increasing unease.
Gutrun	Duchess of Elvritshalla and wife of Duke Isgrimnur, a Rimmersman noblewoman of sharp eyes and red cheeks. Stern, caring, and motherly by nature, she is also temperamental, fussy, and possessed of considerable courage and practical competence. She ran the household at Elvritshalla through the many long absences of her husband, raised their children — including Isorn and three others — and is described by Isgrimnur as a part of himself, the two of them grown together "like two old trees." A capable midwife and manager of a great household, she proves herself resourceful and resilient when adversity demands it.
Gwythinn	A Hernystiri prince and Duke of Hernystir-Duchy, son of King Lluth and half-brother of Maegwin. Tall, handsome, and long-haired with sorrel-colored hair, he is five years younger than Maegwin and deeply attached to his people and land. Impulsive, temperamental, and prideful, Gwythinn embodies Hernystiri defiance in the face of Erkynlandish pressure, quick to anger when his father's realm is threatened.
Haestan	An Erkynlander soldier serving as captain of the guards at Naglimund, assigned by Prince Josua to personally train Simon on his arrival. Burly, broad-backed, and bearlike, with a brown curly beard, he is a simple, hearty man of steady reliability. His practical soldiering, warmth, and patience make him a reassuring presence among Josua's household.
Hengfisk	A Rimmersman monk of the order of Saint Hoderund. Argumentative and proud, he is shaped by the old hostility between Rimmersmen and the Qanuc troll-folk, a prejudice that colors his dealings with Binabik. His piety, stubbornness, and quarrelsome nature make him a sharp contrast to the troll's measured learning.
Hepzibah	An Erkynlander chambermaid at the Hayholt, plump and curly-haired. She belongs to the castle's domestic household, part of the everyday servant world around Simon's youth, and is associated with Lofsunu of the Erkynguard.
Hernystiri	The inhabitants of Hernystir, a human people whose language is Hernystiri and whose old religion is considered pagan by Aedonites. Their kingdom's name is tied to Hern, whose people received lands and royal arms in the Dawn Time, when the Keida'ya still ruled directly over the lands of men. Hernystiri society is feudal; Hernystir was once an independent kingdom and came to acknowledge the suzerainty of the High King. Notable Hernystiri include Eolair, Lluth, Maegwin, Gwythinn, Penemhwye, Fiathna, Inahwen, and Craobhan.
Hjeldin	A Rimmersman king, son of Fingil, and the second of the Six Kings of the Hayholt, counted among the so-called Northern Kings. Known as King Hjeldin the Mad, he was interested in strange arts and allowed his helper-priest Nisses to pursue unusual researches. He is remembered in the Six Kings Rhyme and is closely associated with Hjeldin's Tower at the Hayholt.
Hotvig	A Thrithings-man and Randwarder associated with Clan Mehrdon and the politics of the Three Thrithings. He is a practical rider and messenger, at home among the horse-centered customs and martial life of the Thrithings-folk.
Hunën	Large, shaggy, manlike beings of the Tinukeda'ya people — called giants by most races of Osten Ard and hojun in their own tongue. They were bred apart from the other Tinukeda'ya by the Keida'ya long before their coming to Osten Ard. They are said never to stop growing, and may live at least three hundred years. Their fur is usually white, their skin darker beneath it, their tongues grey, their voices deep and rumbling, their teeth sharp. Some individuals have two heads. They are capable of learning language. Those who dwelt too close to Jao é-Tinukai'i were hunted by the Sithi; those encountered near Nakkiga were enslaved by the Hikeda'ya as war beasts. They are a recurring and dangerous presence in the high mountains of Osten Ard.
Hyara	Younger daughter of March-thane Fikolmij and younger sister of Vorzheva, a woman of the Thrithings tied to the ruling family of Clan Mehrdon.
Hyrka	A wandering people known chiefly as horse-traders and generally regarded as disreputable. They are associated with unsettled travel, trade in horses, and a harsh reputation among other peoples.
Igjarjuk	A great white ice dragon dwelling at the peak of the mountain Urmsheim, daughter of Hidohebhi and sister of Shurakai, with Khaerukama'o as her grandfather. She has served as a boogeyman in the stories of those who live near Urmsheim, with many uncertain whether she still lives. Her appearance is fearsome: a snakelike head as long as a man is tall, piercing blue eyes, a whip-like tail, aged yellowed fur on her back and legs with white scales elsewhere, and black throat, tongue, and blood. She is animalistic in nature.
Inch	An Erkynlander man who works at the Hayholt, first as Doctor Morgenes's helper and then as master of the castle forge. Massive and hugely tall despite his hunched posture, he has a round vacant face, clumsily cut spiky black hair, a thick slow voice, whiskered features, and breath said to smell of stone. Slow-witted in manner but dangerous rather than harmless, he is cruel, temperamental, physically powerful, and almost entirely lacking in displayed empathy.
Ineluki|The Storm King	A Sithi prince of ancient days, son of Iyu'unigato and Amerasu and brother of Hakatri, remembered as the Storm King. In life he was handsome and tall even by the standards of his people, with straight black hair, a quick wit, and a temperament that could be impatient, proud, and easily wounded. His Sithi name means "Here is bright speech." Associated with the great sword Sorrow and with the deepest fears of Osten Ard's peoples, he is a central figure in the old sorrow and enmity surrounding Asu'a, the Sithi, and mankind.
Ingen Jegger	A Black Rimmersman and the Queen's Huntsman of the Norn queen Utuk'ku — the first mortal ever to hold that title, a distinction he bears with fierce pride. Powerfully built, cold-faced, with hair so pale yellow it appears white and eyes of a colourless, possibly blue, hue, he wears a black wolf helmet given to him by Utuk'ku herself as a mark of his station. He is devoted to the queen with an absolute loyalty that admits no other consideration. He is master of the Norn hounds and a relentless tracker, pursuing his quarry across vast distances with implacable patience.
Isgrimnur	Duke of Elvritshalla and one of the great lords of Rimmersgard, a Rimmersman of notable height with huge gnarled hands, a grey beard braided but often tangled from habitual tugging, and a swiftness of movement that surprises those who underestimate his age and stature. He is the son of Isbeorn, from whom he inherited the duchy, and the husband of Gutrun, with whom he shares four children including his eldest son Isorn. He is a cousin of Skali Sharp-nose of Kaldskryke. An Aedonite — his father was the first of his line to convert — he is fiercely loyal, blunt, deeply caring, and driven by a strong sense of honour. Prester John once described him as having "the heart of a bear and the wit of an ox," which he recalls with rueful affection. A trusted friend of Prester John and an uncle-figure to both Elias and Josua, he carries a war-hammer alongside his sword. He is among the tallest figures in Osten Ard.
Isorn	Eldest son of Duke Isgrimnur and Gutrun, heir to Elvritshalla, a Rimmersman with the same blue eyes as his father, broad features, a drawn and shadowed look, and a stock-shouldered, bulky frame. A pious Aedonite, he is skilled with sword and horse. He is on friendly terms with Count Eolair of Hernystir.
Jack Mundwode	A mythical forest bandit, remembered as a figure of outlaw legend rather than as a courtly or noble personage.
Jael	An Erkynlander chambermaid at the Hayholt. She is one of the named servants of the royal castle, part of the domestic household that supports daily life beneath the affairs of kings, priests, guards, and nobles.
Jakob	An Erkynlander chandler at the Hayholt and master to Jeremias. As a castle craftsman, he belongs to the practical working household of the royal stronghold, where tradesmen and servants keep the everyday machinery of Hayholt life functioning.
Jarnauga	A Rimmersman and member of the League of the Scroll, called Iron Eyes. Old, with fierce blue eyes and white hair, he is a man of wisdom and a keeper of deep lore. His father Trestolt was a Scrollbearer before him. He possesses an ability to see great distances, possibly a form of the Art, and is learned in ancient histories, warnings, and the lore preserved by the League.
Jeremias	An Erkynlander boy from the Hayholt, apprenticed to the chandler Jakob. Slow and stumpy, pale, with fine blond hair and a treble chin, he is pessimistic, earnest, and shy. A childhood friend of Simon, he trained alongside him in hopes of becoming a soldier. His skills include chandlery, forging, message-running, singing, and a basic grounding in swordsmanship.
Jiriki i-Sa'onserei|Jiriki	A Sithi prince of Jao é-Tinukai'i, born after the fall of Asu'a and counted among the younger members of his people. Son of Shima'onari and Likimeya, brother of Aditu, and great-nephew of Ineluki. He has golden-brown skin, amber-flecked eyes, and lavender-blue dyed hair, and moves with the fluid, catlike grace characteristic of the Sithi. Together with his sister Aditu he befriended the scholar Tanahaya in their youth. He wields the witchwood sword Indreju. His friendship with Simon began when Simon freed him from a cotsman's trap in the Aldheorte forest; in return, Jiriki loosed a white arrow (Staja Ame) into a nearby tree — the Sithi sign of a life-debt owed.
Josua|Josua Lackhand	A prince of Erkynland and Liege-Lord of Naglimund, younger brother of Elias and uncle to Miriamele. Around thirty-eight at the beginning of The Dragonbone Chair, he is tall and slender, with close-cropped brown hair, a high forehead, hawklike nose, pale grey eyes, and a preference for greyish clothing over royal splendor. Called Josua Lackhand after losing his right hand in a skirmish, he remains a capable swordsman with the slim blade Naidel. Quiet, brooding, studious, melancholy, and self-doubting, he has little desire for power, but his rank and conscience make him an important figure in the troubles surrounding the High King's realm.
Judith	An Erkynlander servant at the Hayholt, serving as cook and Mistress of Kitchens. Her place is in the working heart of the castle household, where the preparation of food and management of the kitchens sustain daily life beneath the royal court. Simon especially remembers her pies.
Kiushapo	A Sitha who accompanies Simon and Jiriki's party to Urmsheim along with Sijandi. He remains at the foot of the mountain to care for the horses.
Leleth	An Erkynlander girl, Miriamele's handmaid, and companion of Geloë. Small and pale, with dark brown eyes, she is quiet and withdrawn in the waking world but unusually expressive in dreams and visions. Her strange connection to the road of dreams gives her a gentle, uncanny presence among those close to Miriamele and Geloë.
Leobardis Benidrivine|Leobardis	Duke of Nabban, a Nabbanai nobleman of the Benidrivine line and brother of Camaris. By the time of The Dragonbone Chair he has long white hair, pink cheeks, mild blue eyes, and a reputation for kindness in Miriamele's memory. He enjoys music and is close to the Aedonite Church. As tensions rise between Elias, Josua, and Nabban, Leobardis attempts to assess the realm's shifting loyalties, sending Baron Devasalles to Naglimund to judge Josua's cause while those nearest him press competing political interests. His house's crest is the golden kingfisher, and his flagship is Emettin's Jewel.
Lezhdraka	A Thrithings-man mercenary chieftain in Fengbald's pay, associated with the armed companies serving the Duke's campaign.
Lluth ubh-Llythinn|Lluth	King of Hernystir, father of Gwythinn and Maegwin. A Hernystiri ruler with a grey moustache, mobile clever features, a crooked nose broken in boyhood, and a lined face, Lluth is usually joyful and smiling and deeply loves his people and land. His court at the Taig includes close liegemen such as Eolair, and his family ties connect him to Llythinn, Ebekah, Penemhwye, Fiathna, Inahwen, Maegwin, and Gwythinn.
Maegwin	Princess of Hernystir, daughter of King Lluth and Penemhwye, and half-sister of Gwythinn. Tall, long-legged, and sorrel-haired, she is insecure about her height and painfully uncertain of Eolair's feelings for her, yet she is also kind, gentle, sensitive, strong, and respected by her people. Lluth trusts her to lead in his absence, and the Hernystiri value her fairness and good judgment. She has skill with animal husbandry, keeps a carved Nightingale token from Lluth, and experiences visions or the road of dreams through the lens of Hernystiri belief.
Mankind|Humans|Sudhoda'ya	The human race living throughout Osten Ard. Humans came across the sea to settle in Osten Ard well after the Sithi had established themselves as masters of the continent. Human peoples include Erkynlanders, Hernystiri, Nabbanai, Perdruinese, Rimmersmen, Thrithings-men, Wrannamen, Hyrka, and the people of Nascadu. The Sithi call mankind Sudhoda'ya, meaning Sunset Children.
Miriamele|Malachias|Marya	An Erkynlander princess, only child and heiress of King Elias and his Nabbanai wife Hylissa. Slender, green-eyed, golden-haired, and gifted with a lovely singing voice, she is kind, guarded, empathetic, clever, and altruistic, though troubled by her father's growing distance under Pryrates's influence. Miriamele often disguises herself, using the name Malachias when passing as a boy and Marya when passing as a servant. Though high-born, she proves resourceful and capable in travel, danger, and courtly maneuvering.
Morgenes Ercestres|Morgenes|Doctor Morgenes	An Erkynlander doctor, scholar, court physician at the Hayholt, and member of the League of the Scroll. Short, blue-eyed, and white-haired, with long bent fingers and a sparse beard, he is intelligent, temperamental, particular, and jovial. He lives in a converted barracks in the Middle Bailey and works on The Life and Reign of King John Presbyter. A practitioner of the Art, he takes Simon as an apprentice, teaching him reading, lore, herbs, and caution rather than the easy magic Simon imagines.
Nabbanai	The inhabitants of Nabban, one of the human peoples of Osten Ard. They have their own Nabbanai tongue and a distinct culture within mankind. Notable Nabbanai include nobles, priests, and members of the Benidrivine and Ingadarine families.
Nessalanta Benedrivine|Nessalanta	Duchess of Nabban, wife of Duke Leobardis, mother of Benigaris, Varellan, and Antippa, and sister of Hylissa. A sternly beautiful Nabbanai noblewoman, she is a shrewd manipulator and politician, with high aspirations and a strong command of courtly presentation through clothing, hairdressing, makeup, and servants. Anyone dealing with the Nabbanai throne must account not only for Leobardis or Benigaris but also for Nessalanta. She is egotistical, superstitious, politically forceful, and interested in astrology.
Nezeru Seyet-Enduya|Nezeru	A half-human Norn and Queen's Talon, daughter of Viyeki and Tzoja. The first and only child of her parents, she is fierce and independent from her earliest days and devoted to making her father proud even when she disagrees with his hopes for her life. Her father's wife Khimabu is her official mother, though their relationship is cool. Like other Hikeda'ya children she is sorted for service, and her unusual survival of that ordeal leads her into the Order of Sacrifice. Her known possession is the sword Cold Root.
Nisses	An Aedonite Black Rimmersman priest who served King Fingil and King Hjeldin. He is associated with esoteric learning and with the old northern court of the Hayholt, where his knowledge made him an adviser in matters beyond ordinary priestly counsel. In Hjeldin's reign he wrote Du Svardenvyrd, also known as The Weird of Swords, a work judged heretical and unholy by the Sancellan Aedonitus.
Norns|Hikeda'ya|Cloud Children	An immortal, human-like Gardenborn people also called the Hikeda'ya, or Cloud Children. Originally part of the Keida'ya with the Sithi, they came from the Garden across the sea to Osten Ard and became distinct from the Zida'ya. They are very pale or ghost-like, with white hair and dark purplish-black eyes. Their culture is centered on Queen Utuk'ku, whom many regard as inseparable from the Hikeda'ya race itself, and on service through formal Orders such as Builders, Sacrifice, Anchoresses, Celebrants, Chroniclers, Singers, and others. Their society is hierarchical, clan-based, and austere, with white or colorless clothing.
Ookequk	A Qanuc wise-man, scholar, Singing Man of Mintahoq and the mountains of Yiqanuc, Scrollbearer, and master of Binabik. Very fat and troll-sized, he is remembered chiefly for his wisdom, his teaching, and his correspondence with Doctor Morgenes. He taught Morgenes how to make birds carry messages, and sets out south with Binabik after signs, bone-castings, and news from Morgenes trouble him. As Singing Man, he stands at the intersection of song, lore, medicine, ceremony, and ancient knowledge among the Qanuc.
Penemhwye	A Hernystiri woman, first wife of King Lluth and mother of Maegwin, remembered through her place in the royal household of Hernystir.
Perdruinese	An inhabitant of Perdruin, associated with the Perdruinese language and also with King John's Westerling tongue after his conquest of Osten Ard. Notable Perdruinese include Sir Tallistro, Count Streáwe, and Lady Faiera.
Prester John|John Presbyter	High King of Osten Ard, Seventh King of the Hayholt, and wielder of the sword Bright-Nail, also called Minneyar or Memory. Born on Warinsten as a commoner, he rose to become the king who brought the realm many years of stability and peace and was remembered for loving his people. In youth he was golden-haired; in character he is reckless, battle-loving, pragmatic, ardently Aedonite, and hostile to the Sithi. His reign bound Nabban, Rimmersgard, Hernystir, and the Thrithings into the political order of the High Ward, and his friendships included Camaris, Isgrimnur, and Towser.
Pryrates|The Red Priest	A hairless, pale, scarlet-robed priest associated with dark magic and the Art, possibly of Naraxi origin. Cruel, manipulative, and cold-eyed, he takes pleasure in pain and is willing to feign subservience when useful. Once considered for the League of the Scroll, he was expelled for his interest in dangerous subjects. Closely tied to Elias and often associated with Hjeldin's Tower and the Hayholt, he pursues hidden lore, alchemy, necromancy, and Words of Changing with heedless appetite.
Qantaqa	A wolf, Binabik's companion, mount, and friend. She travels with him through the dangers surrounding Simon, Josua's company, and the wider struggle across Osten Ard.
Qanuc|Qanuc (People)|Trolls	A diminutive human-like people living in the mountains of Yiqanuc, also called trolls. They are much smaller than ordinary humans and maintain distinctive customs around adulthood, marriage, law, religion, and song. A Qanuc man proposes by placing his spear before a woman's door; adulthood includes a Walk of Manhood or Womanhood; serious disputes may be judged by the Herder and Huntress in the Cave of the Ancestor. Their Singing Men preserve songs, ceremonies, medicine, priestly knowledge, and written lore on hide scrolls. Notable Qanuc include Binabik, Ookequk, Sisqinanamook, Nunuuika, Uammannaq, Chukku, Qangolik, and Snenneq.
Rachel|Rachel the Dragon	Mistress of Chambermaids at the Hayholt, an Erkynlander woman and foster mother of Simon. Called Rachel the Dragon by Simon, she is older, stern, devoutly Aedonite, obsessed with cleanliness, convinced of the value of hard work, and formidable to lazy scullions. Rachel helps raise Simon with the other chambermaids and Morgenes. Her practical authority, knowledge of the Hayholt, and fierce maternal concern make her one of the castle's most memorable servants.
Ranessin|Oswine of Stanshire	Lector of the Aedonite Church, born Oswine of Stanshire in Erkynland and raised to the highest office of Mother Church through Prester John's influence. Nearly seventy, slender, pale, grey-haired, and bright-eyed, he is gentle, humble, extremely clever, and a fearsome debater. He dislikes pomp, preferring to walk rather than be carried on ceremonial occasions, and attempts to remain outwardly neutral amid political conflict while working subtly for peace. Father Dinivan serves as his secretary.
Rimmersmen	The inhabitants of Rimmersgard. Most converted to the Aedonite Church after King John's conquest, though historically they followed Rimmersman paganism. They are associated with a cold northern homeland, common use of furs, and the language Rimmerspakk. Notable Rimmersmen include Gutrun, Hengfisk, Ingen Jegger, Isgrimnur, Isorn, Jarnauga, Skali, and Sludig.
Sangfugol	An Erkynlander harper and musician at Josua's court in Naglimund. Young, slender, dark-haired, fond of fine clothing, and skilled with harp, lute, and song, he has a wide knowledge of the songs and stories of Osten Ard. Boisterous, anxious, mischievous, and not especially brave, he is nevertheless loyal to Josua and perceptive about the prince's self-doubt, often wishing Josua would act more firmly. He befriends Simon and spends much time in the company of the old jester Towser.
Sarrah	A fair-haired Erkynlander chambermaid at the Hayholt. She is part of the castle's servant household, one of the named domestic workers who form the ordinary world surrounding Simon's early life in the royal stronghold.
Seriddan Metessis|Seriddan	Baron of Metessa, a Nabbanai nobleman whose barony lies north of Lake Clodu and borders the Lake Thrithings. Also known in Nabbanai as Seriddan Metessis, he is older brother of Brindalles and uncle of Pasevalles. He has shrewd eyes, a sun-browned bearded peasant face, and a roguishly dangerous look unusual among Nabbanai nobles. His lands are prosperous, crossed by a branch of the Stefflod, and centered on the hilltop keep Chasu Metessa. The heraldic bird of the Metessans is a blue heron.
Shem Horsegroom	An Erkynlander groom at the Hayholt. His role places him among the castle's stable servants, responsible for the care of horses and the practical work that supports travel, messengers, guards, and noble households.
Shurakai	A red dragon associated with the deep history beneath the Hayholt. Huge as a house, with red-golden scales and teeth as long as Simon's hand, she is a daughter of Hidohebhi and sister of Igjarjuk. Her blood is caustic enough to burn through flesh and bone, and she breathes fire. Royal legend connects her with the older mysteries and dragon-lore of the castle.
Sijandi	A Sitha who accompanies Simon and Jiriki's party to Urmsheim along with Kiushapo. Like Kiushapo, he remains at the foot of the mountain to care for the horses.
Simon|Seoman|Snowlock	A young Erkynlander, born Seoman and called Simon, fourteen years old at the beginning of The Dragonbone Chair. Red-haired, freckled, blue-eyed, tall and thin-framed, he is a scullion at the Hayholt raised by Rachel and watched over by Doctor Morgenes. Naive, anxious, childish, brave, and prone to daydreaming, he hungers for stories, glory, and magic. Morgenes takes him as an apprentice, teaching reading, herbs, history, and caution rather than the easy wizardry Simon imagines. His curiosity about the Hayholt's hidden ways draws him into the larger mysteries of Osten Ard.
Sinetris	A Perdruinese boatman living on the coast above the Wran. He transports Isgrimnur to Kwanitupul.
Sisqinanamook|Sisqi	A Qanuc warrior, daughter of Uammannaq the Herder and Nunuuika the Huntress, rulers of Yiqanuc, and betrothed to Binabik. She has glossy black hair plaited on either side of her face and joined beneath her chin with a sky-blue ribbon, brown skin, little jewelry, and a single blue gem on her forehead held by a leather thong. Strong-willed, comely, and clever, she is a notable Qanuc woman whose family ties place her close to the leadership of her people.
Sithi|Zida'ya|Dawn Children	An immortal, human-like Gardenborn people who came to Osten Ard long before humanity. They call themselves Zida'ya, or Dawn Children, while humans know them as Sithi and Hernystiri call them the Peaceful Ones. Golden-skinned, slender, graceful, with large amber cat-like eyes, prominent cheekbones, and naturally white hair often dyed bright colors, they do not age as mortals do. Their history begins in the Garden with the Keida'ya, divides between Zida'ya and Hikeda'ya, and continues through exile across the sea, the founding of great cities, conflict and friendship with mortal peoples, and hidden refuges such as Jao é-Tinukai'i.
Skali Sharp-nose|Skali	A Rimmersman thane of Kaldskryke and kinsman of Duke Isgrimnur, called Sharp-nose. Yellow-bearded and politically favored by Elias at Isgrimnur's expense, he is an ambitious northern lord whose standing reflects the shifting loyalties and rivalries of Rimmersgard.
Sludig	A Rimmersman soldier in Duke Isgrimnur's service and a companion of Simon and Binabik from Naglimund. Fair-haired, yellow-bearded, pale blue-eyed, dutiful, pragmatic, and clever, he is initially wary of close fellowship, especially with a Qanuc troll, but proves a resilient travel companion. He teaches Simon practical combat lessons on the road, and around campfires sometimes sings both bawdy and heartfelt songs.
Strangyeard	Father Strangyeard, an Erkynlander Aedonite priest, scholar, archivist, and historian at Naglimund. Slight, pale, and long-chinned, with sparse red hair, one blue eye, and a black eyepatch, he is shy, bumbling, distracted, and highly intelligent. His strengths are scholarship, archives, and patient lore-work rather than worldly confidence, and he is drawn to the old histories and manuscripts that surround Josua's court.
Streáwe	Count of Perdruin, lord of Ansis Pelippé and master of the island. White-haired, aged, physically frail, and carried in a litter because his legs no longer work, he is nevertheless iron-willed, manipulative, jovial, temperamental, and supremely skilled at politics. He presents weakness when useful and uses Perdruin's neutrality, information networks, wealth, servants, gardens, and trained messenger birds to bargain with every side. One of the wealthiest men in Osten Ard, he believes those lacking physical strength must survive through intelligence.
Susanna	An Erkynlander chambermaid at the Hayholt, dark-haired and dark-eyed, wife of Eahlferend and mother of Simon. Her connection to Doctor Morgenes and the scroll pendant associated with her make her a small but meaningful figure in Simon's early background.
Tallistro, Sir|Sir Tallistro	A famous Perdruinese knight of John Presbyter's Great Table, remembered in connection with the First Thrithings War.
The Hidden	A mysterious group of Tinukeda'ya living in Nakkiga, associated with Jijibo's experiments. They are grotesquely varied in body shape, with limbs and orifices in strange places, aversion to bright light, and the ability to speak. Named figures include Naya Nos, Dasa, and Uvasika, called Mistress of the Hidden and the Silent Lady.
Thrithings-man|Thrithings-men|Randwarders	The nomadic clans-people of the Three Thrithings, also called randwarders. Their wagon-travelling culture is strongly centered on horses, with wealth measured by herd quality and size, and strength viewed as the paramount measure of a man. Thrithings society is heavily male-dominated, suspicious of town-dwelling "stone-dwellers," and governed by old clan laws concerning leadership, marriage, and custom. Clans gather at Blood Lake for the Thanemoot, a midsummer festival with markets, contests, riding, wrestling, and other feats. Notable Thrithings-folk include Vorzheva, Fikolmij, Hotvig, Hyara, and Lezhdraka.
Tiamak	A Wrannaman scholar and member of the League of the Scroll. Short and brown-skinned, scholarly, skeptical of religion, and somewhat alienated from his own people, he was the first of his village to leave the Wran to study with the Usirean Brothers in Ansis Pelippé. There he learned Nabbanai and befriended Doctor Morgenes, whom he came to revere. Tiamak studies healing lore and works on The Sovran Remedies of the Wranna Healers, exchanging letters by messenger bird with other scholars. He can travel the Wran on stilts and is fluent in Perdruinese as well as Erkynlandish.
Tinukeda'ya|Vao|Ocean Children|Changelings	A diverse Gardenborn people who call themselves Vao and are also known as Ocean Children or Changelings. They include many races, among them Dwarrow, Niskies, Hunën, Chikri, Ghants, Kilpa, the Hidden, and Cary Men. Historically servants and slaves of the Keida'ya, they came from the Garden to Osten Ard and built all of the Nine Sithi cities. Though denied the near-immortality of the Sithi and Norns, they are very long-lived and unusually adaptable, taking on traits shaped by the places and peoples among whom they live. Notable Tinukeda'ya include Gan Itai, Valada Geloë, Ruyan Vé, Yis-fidri, and Yis-hadra.
Tiyagaris	A Nabbanai ruler remembered as the first Imperator. His entry places him at the head of Nabban's imperial tradition, marking him as an early figure of authority in the history of one of Osten Ard's major human powers.
Towser|Cruinh	An Erkynlander jester in long service to Prester John and attached to Josua's company. His true name is Cruinh, but he took the name Towser after a jest involving one of King John's hounds. Elderly, bald, wrinkled, bent in posture and legs, fond of wine, and often dreary beneath his silliness, he plays lute, sings sweetly, and has a deep store of songs, verse, and memories of the old days of the realm.
Utuk'ku Seyt-Hamakha|Utuk'ku	Queen of the Norns of Stormspike and mistress of Nakkiga, wife of the late Ekimeniso Blackstaff and mother of Drukhi. The oldest living creature born in the Garden, she is at least ten thousand years old and the central figure of Hikeda'ya reverence. Once beautiful, now very thin with prominent bones and paper-white skin, she wears a famous silver mask. Spiteful, cruel, manipulative, and shaped by ancient mourning, she rules a society that treats obedience to her as sacred duty. Her people call her Mother of All and organize much of their law, ritual, and service around her will.
Valada Geloë|Geloë	A blunt-spoken wise woman of the Aldheorte with a reputation as a witch, calling herself Protectress of the Forest. Likely Tinukeda'ya, she lives in a lonely lake-house that seems to Simon to have giant clawed feet beneath it. Not very tall, broad-faced, sun-browned, with short hair once black and now grey-shot, a sharp downward-curving nose, heavy-lidded yellow eyes, and a posture of strength, she is wise, terse, and formidable. She communes with nature, walks the dream-road, knows the League of the Scroll, and can use aspects of the Art including owl-shape, bird-speech, wind-summoning, and dream travel.
Varellan	A Nabbanai nobleman of the Benidrivine bloodline, youngest son of Leobardis and Nessalanta, brother of Benigaris and Antippa, and cousin of Miriamele through Hylissa. Handsome, tall, thin, pale, watery-eyed, timid, stubborn, honorable, and apologetic in posture, he is more naturally suited to priesthood than war. Mocked for priestly inclinations, he turns toward a military career largely to impress his father, despite being ill-suited to it. He carries the Warmaster's baton of the Benidrivine house.
Velligis	A Nabbanai Aedonite priest and Escritor. Very large and fat, with a round head, he is politic, deferential, cunning in a cautious way, and able to talk at length while saying little. He places himself near whoever seems likely to prevail, aware of political mutterings around Elias and Leobardis but rarely useful to those seeking decisive action. He often carries a box of sweets and is moved by an eight-man litter.
Viyeki Seyet-Enduya|Viyeki	A Norn lord and High Magister of the Order of Builders, full name Viyeki set-Enduya. White-haired, alabaster-skinned, black-eyed, with defined cheeks and jaw, he is a skilled engineer descended from Enduyo of Kementari. Son of the justiciar and admired court artist Urayeki, he is closely tied to the Builders and their craft in Nakkiga. His family includes Khimabu, his daughter Nezeru, and Tzoja, his favored mortal concubine.
Vorzheva	A Thrithings-woman of Clan Mehrdon, daughter of Fikolmij and sister of Hyara, and companion of Prince Josua. Tall, slender, dark-eyed, ivory-skinned, with raven-black curly hair and a hawklike nose, she values elegance and works hard to assert her place as lady of Naglimund despite prejudice from others. Willful, intelligent, quick-tempered, and shaped by a culture where women have little formal power, she is driven by love, pride, and a fierce desire for women to have a voice in decisions that shape the world.
Wrannaman|Wrannamen	The inhabitants of the Wran, a short, brown-skinned human people living in tribal villages amid marsh and watercourse. Wrannamen families are large, often with several generations in one or two stilted huts. They travel by boat or stilt, wear breechclouts and robes in the hot climate, trap crabs and swamp creatures, fish, forage yellowroot and fern, brew fern beer, and bake flat breads on hot stones. Their houses are built on stilts with bark roofs, and clay potters make bowls for food and drink. Their villages are governed by elders, and tribal duty weighs heavily.
Xorastra	A Perdruinese innkeeper, former Aedonite nun, Scrollbearer, and proprietress of Pelippa's Bowl in Kwanitupul. Fiercely clever, sharp-eyed, devout, and scholarly, she left her order while remaining religious. She befriended Morgenes and joined the League of the Scroll, putting forward Dinivan and Pryrates as candidates when the League sought seven members. Pelippa's Bowl passes from her household to her niece Charystra.
Yis-fidri	A Dwarrow of the Tinukeda'ya and keeper of Pattern Hall, married to Yis-hadra. He belongs to the Dwarrow branch of the Vao, the people associated with hidden halls, stonework, metalwork, and Mezutu'a.
Yis-hadra	A Dwarrow of the Tinukeda'ya and keeper of Pattern Hall, married to Yis-fidri. She belongs to the Dwarrow branch of the Vao, the people associated with hidden halls, stonework, metalwork, and Mezutu'a.
